The government has so far spent Sh220 million on the livestock offtake programme, in which 1,800 animals have already been bought.Livestock PS Andrew Tuimur yesterday said Kenya Meat Commission has received Sh170 million of the amount and 1,500 cattle have been bought in Kilifi, Tana River and Samburu counties. Sh50 million was given to ADC, which has bought 300 cattle. &ldquo;We received Sh650 million for the first phase as part of drought interventions. A total of Sh230 million went towards buying feed supplements, 67 per cent of which will be delivered to 20 arid and semi-arid counties,&rdquo; he said.a total of Sh200 million will go towards disease management, including buying vaccines.The second phase of the programme will run from the end January until February for Sh713 million, while the third phase will start from March to May for Sh651 million.Briefing the press on drought and food situation in Kenya, Devolution Cabinet Secretary Mwangi Kiunjuri said five counties have reported livestock deaths associated with drought.Garissa, Marsabit, Samburu, West Pokot and Lamu are the most affected counties.&ldquo;Foot and mouth disease has been reported in Baringo, Isiolo, Kajiado, Kwale, Lamu, Marsabit, Meru, Narok, Samburu and Taita Taveta. Contagious bovine pleuropneumonia disease was reported in Taita Taveta and some areas of Garissa, Narok and Kajiado,&rdquo; Kiunjuri said.The CS said the drought is worsening because by October last year, only five counties were of concern, but the number has risen to 11.&ldquo;The livestock sector is particularly at risk because the coastal region is usually the dry season grazing fall-back and it is currently experiencing severe drought. Further, cross border migrations are limited because neighbouring countries are also affected,&rdquo; he said. Kiunjuri said by November last year, the government, through the National Treasury, released Sh1.8 billion of the Sh5.4 million for the first phase which runn until this month.&ldquo;The first disbursement was directed to the livestock, agriculture, water, health and nutrition, special programmes and drought coordination sectors. The second phase will run from February to April for Sh9 billion and the third phase from May to July for Sh7 billion,&rdquo; he said.